Recent research demonstrates that utilizing signal jitter to exploit cryptographic circuits has emerged as a critical side-channel vulnerability. The jitter-based side-channel analysis (JitSCA) attack measures signal jitter emanating from cryptographic circuits using time-to-digital converters (TDCs), potentially demonstrating the ability to conduct a remote attack. This paper proposes JitFilt, the first countermeasure to mitigate JitSCA attacks. The JitFilt constructs signal jitter filters using Field Programmable Gate Array (FPGA) mixed mode clock managers (MMCMs), phase-locked loops (PLLs), and IDELAY components to reduce signal jitter.We demonstrate the proposed JitFilt countermeasure on a Digilent ZedBoard FPGA platform. We validate the efficacy of JitFilt’s ability to safeguard cryptographic circuits against JitSCA attacks using Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) circuits. Our results show that the PLL-based clock filter implementation (JitFilt-PLL) demonstrates the highest protection against JitSCA attacks and protects the secret key for up to five million traces. At the same time, an unprotected AES encryption setup would reveal the secret key within 30,000 encryptions, demonstrating over 166× protection.